        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-08-03T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-08-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="81"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d81">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">756D.94/42: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-03T14:00:00+09:00"
                            >August 3, 1940—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 3—8 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>658. In our immediately following telegram 659, August 3, 3 p.m. we report the
                    substance of a communication received from Consul Bruner at Nagoya based upon a
                    conversation with Mr. Arthur Thomas Porghesse<note n="7" xml:id="d81fn7">A
                        naturalized American citizen.</note> who is the subject of the Department’s
                    instruction No. 1845, November 25, 1939.<note n="8" xml:id="d81fn8">Not found in
                        Department files.</note> Bruner states that Porghesse probably obtained his
                    information from Takehito Chikui who is Director of the Mutsuwa Shokai which is
                    believed to have been established to further the interests of the younger
                    elements in the Japanese Army. This is probably the case as the views expressed
                    in the following report are undoubtedly held by the younger army elements but
                    they are not necessarily shared by the High Command.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
